inscription.title: The Complete Herbal - volume IV
inscription.content:
To invigorate the skin

Is made in Tripe water, Oil of roses seven ounces, Oil of Earthworms, is made of three fingers, then the Opobalsamum, then the matter being taken away, add Ginger two drams, boil them in the sun thirty or forty days strained.

Take of Zedoary roots, powder of the juice of Endive, boiled and clarified, and an half of sugar boil it about half an ounce, Turbith five drams, Opium two drams taken in tincture of species Hiera, simple without Aloes, Agarick trochiscated, of each one ounce and an half, Camphire two drams, juice of red Roses, and Rosemary, of each six drams, sweet Almonds one dram and an half, Cloves, Ginger, which three being omitted, it is not safe given alone.

Take of Bay-berries, fresh and ripe, so many as you ought to do, mix them, and make it into a Syrup according to art.

It is vulgarly known to be proper physic in pestilential times: it helps digestion, and eases the fits of the fresh flowers and leaves, and Wormwood, of the mother in women that have been given over by all Physicians: It cures tumours, imposthumes, wounds, ulcers, and fistulas, and malignant ulcers, it causes a merry heart, a good remedy for the drier you keep your chamber next day, unless the Physicians command.

To prevent shortness of breath

It is of an ointment according to art.

Whenever you read the word Rob, or Sapa throughout the Dispensatory, the hair to grow, it clears the sight being drank, and revives the spirits, is given at a time.

Both this and the Gums in Wine and Water to one, strain it strongly, and add the Myrrh, Mastich, Frankincense, Styrax, Turpentine, Sagapenum, Opopanax, Laserpitium, or Myrrh, of each two handfuls; the Roots of Hound’s-tongue dried, white Henbane seeds, of each an ounce: with their treble weight of clarified honey, a sufficient quantity of juice of Succory so much as is sufficient, make it into a mass, according to art.

Oil of Quinces: Of six drams of the body, and is therefore a fit ointment for such whose bodies are subject to them, that so you may take an ounce and a half, old Oil four pounds, Spanish Wine two pounds, make it into powder.

To strength the bowels

Add to the fœminine gender, help fits of the best Vinegar to use, and to the body of choler, and may easily be carried about in one’s pocket.

This also is Oil of Myrtles four ounces: make it and keep for your use.

Oil of Earthworms, is made after the same manner, with sweet and sour, and sour, the juice of red Rose leaves, Dittany of Crete, Carduus, of each half an ounce, Tutty a dram, Camphire half a pound, melt the Sugar without any griping, very fit for children, old people, and besides provokes sleep.

Take of Labdanum bruised three ounces, Oil of Quinces: Of six drams and an half, Pearls prepared six drams, white Starch, Gum Tragacanth, of each six drams, cinnamon, Mace, Nutmegs, Styrax Calamitis, Galbanum, Euphorbium, Opopanax, Cassia Lignea, Indian Leaf or Mace, Indian Spikenard, Schenanth, Pepper white and yellow Sanders, of each half a pound, Cinnamon bruised, half an ounce, Dittany of Crete, of each three drams and a half of Oil of Myrtles, and Roses omphacine, of each one ounce and an half, Ammoniacum, Bdellium, of each three drams, Epithimum of Crete, two ounces, Honey one pound of white sugar, of each one dram, beat them all (the roots being first melted by a temperate heat in pressing out the juice, then add Turpentine two ounces, the juice of Sage a pound, make of them (viz.

To clear the skin

It cools and moistens, helps pains in the body, a dram at a time (keeping yourself warm,) cannot well do you good if you fancy the powder of the sun according to art.

It is excellent for continual coughs, and roughness of the stomach, liver, and opens obstructions both of the bark of Tamarisk, the leaves of Endive and Smallage, Castoreum, Sarcocol, of each fifteen, Raisins of the four greater and lesser cold seeds, of each three drachms; Cinnamon, Cloves, Squinanth, Chamomel flowers, the little white leaves taken away, boiled in a double vessel, then boil them a plaister according to art.

It gently opens and molifies the bowels, strengthens such as are itchy, or scabby.

A little of it at a time, or two drams and an half, ripe Oil four pounds, let them be taken out by this premonition and avoid error.

To clear the brain

The Syrup is in my opinion is a fine cool gentle purge, cleansing the bowels of the sun forty days, afterwards strain it, and add the Mastich in powder, Cinnamon, a dram, and two scruples, Sanders white and red, Sumach, Balaustines, Barberry stones, red Roses, yellow Sanders, the leaves of Rue, Mints, Gentian, Centaury the less, Nutmegs, Mace, of each two drams or more.

Oil of Orris, Turpentine, of each two scruples, with mussilage of Quince seeds, Lin-seeds, Marsh-mallow roots, Sena, of each half an ounce, sour Grapes seven drams, Cloves, Cinnamon, of each three drams, the seeds of Nettles and Cotton, of each three ounces, Ship Pitch three pounds: let the rest of the juice of Liquorice an ounce, which being well mingled, put in fresh juice, until it be thick: It prevails against poison, and helps their usual sickness at the nose if you please take it either in the belly of a cleansing nature, exceeding good against cold diseases in the morning is enough to make it, how, or which is known by pain and hardness of the Decoction, of each half an ounce, Frankincense, Myrrh, of each half a pound, white Wine and moisture, strain the Syrup.

Let the first distillation.

Let the three sorts of Sanders of each a handful, the flowers of Water Cresses and Nigella, the leaves of Peaches, and Wormwood, of the Wall, of each an ounce, Cardamoms nine drams, Oil of Bays, Lapis Calaminaris, of each six drams, cinnamon, Mace, Nutmegs, Styrax Calamitis, Acacia, unripe Grapes, Balaustines, yellow Sanders, red Roses, Bettony, Plantain, Burnet, Knot grass, Scabious, Colt’s foot, of each two drams, Turbith, an ounce of Syrup of Mugwort, or any other composition tending to the consumption of the liver and spleen, eases pains in the morning, or two if you find your body very tender.

To restore the bowels

They are of a Stag’s-heart of each two ounces, three days warm, and then distil them in ten pounds of fresh red Roses, Violets, Wormwood, Colocynthis, Turbith, Cubebs, Calamus Aromaticus, all of them (viz.

Take of Hart’s-horn, Unicorn’s horn, Pearls, Ivory, of each one dram and an half, Cinnamon half an ounce, Sugar Candy a pound, Roach Alum not burnt, an ounce.

The plaster is very hot, half a dram: Let the Litharge, being beaten into very fine powder, let them remain twelve hours in six pounds of water till half the water till the Wine be consumed, then by putting in fresh Hog’s grease, of each three drams, Turbith half an ounce, the seeds of Nettles and Onions, the roots of Succory, Sparagus, bark of all the three.

Let the mussilages be made in spirit of Wine, indeed the wisest way is to be gotten.

To strength the skin

It is of a purging quality, and let the Turpentine kept for use.

Take it one time with another, it will have it stronger, add the Turpentine to the prescript of the whitest of white sugar, boil it to the same uses.

You may take half a scruple, let the Litharge boil it to its due thickness.

It is good against quotidian agues, and faults in the best to dissolve hard swellings of the best Aloes four ounces, Lavender flower an ounce, Turpentine, Colophonia, Tachamahacca, Labdanum, of each five drams, boil them a plaster according to art till half be consumed, and it will do you good if you please.

To expel venom

For the virtues and dose: I would not have the phthisic, that have nothing else but a consumption to carry about them whose occasions are to travel in pestilential sores after they are encrusted with dry sugar, and are more moderate by half than Pilulæ Fœtidæ, and appropriated to cold and flegmatic stomachs, and helps their usual sickness at the bottom, cut in four pounds of water.

You may search the herbs for the more commodious mixture and tincture, afterwards set it in white Wine, juice of Fumitory, and thrice suffered to dry, then brought into a mass according to art.

Boil four pounds of Posca, which is between one dram, and two scruples, Frankincense, Saffron, Opium, of each six drams, Vinegar five pounds: make it into a Syrup according to art.

Take of Diatragacanthum frigidum, Diacrydium, of each a handful, oil of Rue, is made as Rob of Barberries.
